title:
Term structure shapes and their consistent dynamics in the Svensson
  family

sections.text:
#### Abstract

We examine the shapes attainable by the forward- and yield-curve in the widely-used Svensson family, including the NelsonSiegel and Bliss subfamilies. We provide a complete classification of all attainable shapes and partition the parameter space of each family according to these shapes. Building upon these results, we then examine the consistent dynamic evolution of the Svensson family under absence of arbitrage. Our analysis shows that consistent dynamics further restrict the set of attainable shapes, and we demonstrate that certain complex shapes can no longer appear after a deterministic time horizon. Moreover a single shape (either inverse of normal curves) must dominate in the long-run.

## 1. INTRODUCTION

The Nelson-Siegel and the Svensson family are parametric interpolation families for yield curves and forward curves, which are widely used by national banks and other financial institutions [BfIS05]. The Nelson-Siegel family [NS87] expresses the forward curve as a linear combination of three basis functions, commonly associated to level, slope and curvature in the form

$$
\phi_{N S}(x)=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1} \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau}\right)+\frac{\beta_{2}}{\tau} x \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau}\right)
$$

Svensson [Sve95] argues that this family is not flexible enough to reproduce more complex shapes with multiple humps and dips ${ }^{1}$, as they are frequently encountered in the market, and adds another curvature term with a different time-scale $\tau_{2} \neq \tau_{1}$, resulting in

$$
\phi_{S}(x)=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1} \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau_{1}}\right)+\frac{\beta_{2}}{\tau_{1}} x \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau_{1}}\right)+\frac{\beta_{3}}{\tau_{2}} x \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau_{2}}\right)
$$

A further interpolation family, due to Bliss [Bli96], is obtained by setting $\beta_{2}=0$ in the Svensson parametrization. Here, we are interested in the term

structure shapes ${ }^{2}$ that can be represented by the Svensson family of curves and by its subfamilies (Nelson-Siegel, Bliss). The shape of the term structure is a fundamental economic indicator and it encodes important information on market preferences for short-term vs. long-term investments, on expectations of central bank decisions and on the general economic outlook. Decreasing ('inverse') shapes of the term structure, for example, have been identified as signals of economic recessions, see [BM18]. On the other hand, complex shapes with multiple local extrema have frequently been observed in both US and Euro area markets, see e.g. [GSW07] or [DK20, App. B]. Two exemplary yield curves from the Euro area are shown in Fig. 1.

Despite the wide adoption of the Svensson family, some of its basic properties relating to term-structure shapes have never been systematically studied, such as these simple questions:
Q1: Which shapes, exactly, can be represented by the Svensson family, and which cannot?
Q2: What is the shape of the forward curve and the yield curve for a given parameter vector $\beta=\left(\beta_{0}, \beta_{1}, \beta_{2}, \beta_{3}\right)$ ?
Q3: Under a consistent dynamic evolution ${ }^{3}$ of the Svensson family, which shapes are observed with strictly positive probability?
We will refer to the the first question as the classification problem, the second question as the segmentation problem (asking for a segmentation of the parameter space according to shape) and the third question as the consistent dynamics problem. While partial answers to these problems can certainly be given by numerical experiment, we are aiming for more general and systematic answers: We want to understand how the parameter space $\Theta=\left\{\beta:\left(\beta_{0}, \beta_{1}, \beta_{2}, \beta_{3}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{4}\right\}$ of the Svensson family decomposes into regions $R_{1}, \ldots, R_{k}$, such that each region is associated to a certain shape of the forward curve or the yield curve, and how frequently these regions are visited by the corresponding stochastic factor process under a consistent dynamic simulation. Despite the apparent simplicity of questions Q1-Q3, it seems that such systematic results are currently missing from the literature ${ }^{4}$, and we intend to close this gap with this paper.

Before providing mathematical details and methods, we give an overview of our results. First, as a simple observation, the Svensson family (with

$$
\phi_{S}(x)=\beta_{0}+\beta_{3}\left(\gamma_{\Pi} \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau_{1}}\right)+\frac{\gamma_{\mathrm{I}}}{\tau_{1}} x \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau_{1}}\right)+\frac{1}{\tau_{2}} x \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau_{2}}\right)\right)

where we have set

$$
\gamma=\left(\gamma_{\mathrm{I}}, \gamma_{\mathrm{II}}\right)=\left(\frac{\beta_{2}}{\beta_{3}}, \frac{\beta_{1}}{\beta_{3}}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{2}

As an additive shift, $\beta_{0}$ has no influence on the term structure's shape. Moreover, the scaling factor $\beta_{3}$ will only influence the shape through its sign. Thus, to answer questions Q1-Q3, the effective parameter space can be reduced to the two-dimensional space

$$
\Theta^{\prime}=\left\{\gamma: \gamma \in \mathbb{R}^{2}\right\}
$$

Furthermore, it will turn out that two phase transitions in the Svensson family's behaviour will take place, depending on the ratio

$$
r=\frac{\tau_{1}}{\tau_{2}}
$$

of time-scales.
Definition 2.1. We distinguish the following regimes:

- $r>1$ : scale-regular (sr),
- $r \in[1 / 3,1)$ : weakly scale-inverted (wsi), and
- $r \in(0,1 / 3)$ : strongly scale-inverted (ssi).
2.1. The classification and segmentation problems. Our first main results answer the question Q1 of shape classification. We start with a basic result, which is easy to obtain from arguments based on Tchebycheff systems, see Sec. 3.3:

Theorem 2.2. The forward curve and the yield curve have
(1) at most a single local extremum in the Nelson-Siegel family,
(2) at most two local extrema in the Bliss family, and
(3) at most three local extrema in the Svensson family.

Note that this result gives only necessary, but no sufficient conditions for a particular shape to appear. To give a more refined picture, we call a term structure shape (in the sense of Table 1) attainable, if there exists a parameter $\beta \in \Theta$ such that the corresponding yield curve or forward curve in the Svensson family exhibits this shape. The same terminology also applies in the Bliss family, the Nelson-Siegel family, or under other parameter restrictions, e.g. when the sign of $\beta_{3}$ is restricted.

Theorem 2.3. The following statements hold for both the yield curve and the forward curve in the Svensson family:
(a) In the scale-regular regime the shapes normal, inverse, dipped and humped are attainable for any $\beta_{3} \in \mathbb{R}$. If $\beta_{3}>0$ also the shapes $h d$ and $h d h$ are attainable; if $\beta_{3}<0$ also the shapes $d h$ and $d h d$.
(b) In the weakly scale-inverted regime the shapes inverse, humped and $d h$ are attainable if $\beta_{3}>0$. The shapes normal, dipped and $h d$ are attainable if $\beta_{3}<0$.

(c) In the strongly scale-inverted regime the shapes inverse, humped, $d h$ and hdh are attainable if $\beta_{3}>0$. The shapes normal, dipped, hd, dhd are attainable if $\beta_{3}<0$.

In this attainability result, it is not necessary to distinguish between yield curve and forward curve. The segmentation of the parameter space, however, will differ between these cases. We illustrate regime (a) in Fig. 2, regime (b) in Fig. 7, and regime (c) in Fig. 8. All analytic results on the segmentation problem can be found in Section 5. Note that the case $\beta_{3}=0$ excluded in Theorem 2.3 corresponds to the Nelson-Siegel family and is treated in Section 3.2. Further results on the Bliss family $\left(\beta_{2}=0\right)$ can be found in Section 5.4. Finally, we remark, that even when a particular shape is attainable, it may be attainable only for a very narrow range of parameters. See for example the tiny spot in Fig. 2B that corresponds to three local extrema (hdh).

Remark 2.4. Note that the segmentation of $\Theta^{\prime}$ is independent of $\beta_{3}$, but changing the sign of $\beta_{3}$ will reverse the 'polarity' of each region, in the sense that local minima and local maxima of the forward curve are interchanged.
2.2. Empirical observations. The ECB publishes yield curves and forward curves, modelled with the Svensson family, on a daily basis. To complement our theoretical results, we present a brief overview of term structure regimes and shapes observed for AAA-rated bonds in the Euro Area from September 06th, 2004 to September 24th, 2024.

In Fig. 3 we show how the value of $r$, see (2.3), changes over time. The plot shows that every regime from Definition 2.1 is attained. More precisely, the regimes are attained with the following relative frequencies.

$$
\begin{array}{lllll}
\beta_{3}>0: & \text { sr: } & 2.2 \%, & \text { wsi: } & 2.0 \%, & \text { ssi: } & 6.7 \%, \\
\beta_{3}<0: & \text { sr: } & 46.0 \%, & \text { wsi: } & 35.0 \%, & \text { ssi: } & 8.1 \%
\end{array}
$$

In Fig. 4 we show how the shape of the yield curve and the forward curve change over time. Every shape with at most 3 local extrema, except the inverse shape, is attained. More precisely, the yield curve attains the shapes with the following relative frequencies

$$
\begin{array}{llllllll}
\mathrm{n}: & 19.2 \%, & \mathrm{~h}: & 7.9 \%, & \mathrm{hd}: & 13.0 \%, & \mathrm{hdh}: & 5.0 \% \\
\mathrm{i}: & 0.0 \%, & \mathrm{~d}: & 25.0 \%, & \mathrm{dh}: & 29.4 \%, & \mathrm{dhd}: & 0.5 \%
\end{array}
$$

and for the forward curve the values change to

$$
\begin{array}{llllllllll}
\mathrm{n}: & 11.6 \%, & \mathrm{~h}: & 10.1 \%, & \mathrm{hd}: & 18.1 \%, & \mathrm{hdh}: & 5.3 \% \\
\mathrm{i}: & 0.0 \%, & \mathrm{~d}: & 13.6 \%, & \mathrm{dh}: & 39.7 \%, & \mathrm{dhd}: & 1.6 \%
\end{array}
$$

2.3. Consistent dynamic evolution of term-structure shapes. The question of the consistency of a family of parametrized forward rate curves with the arbitrage-free dynamic evolution of interest rates has been initiated by Björk and Christensen in [BC99] and has been answered in the particular cases of the Nelson-Siegel and the Svensson family by Filipovic in [Fil99] and [Fil00]. For the consistency problem, we consider a dynamic

It turns out, that the scope of Ito-processes (2.4), which fulfill the requirement of consistency, is substantially restricted, and can be essentially reduced to a single-factor short rate model with time-dependent coefficients (again, we refer to [Fil00] and [Fil09, Ch. 9] for details). Here, in answering question Q3, we are

interested in the restrictions on the shapes of term-structure curves imposed by the consistency requirement, and obtain the following result:

Theorem 2.5. In the consistent dynamic Svensson-model with initial forward curve given by (1.2) the following holds:
(1) If $\beta_{2}>0$ then there is a time-horizon

$$
T_{\uparrow}^{\mathrm{f}}=\max \left(-\frac{5}{2}+\log \left(\frac{4 \beta_{3}}{\beta_{2}}\right), 0\right)
$$

such that the forward curve attains each of the shapes inverse, humped and hdh with strictly positive probability at any time $t<T_{\uparrow}$, and each of the shapes inverse, humped with strictly positive probability at any time $t>T_{\uparrow}$. All other shapes are almost surely never attained.
(2) If $\beta_{2}<0$ then there is a time-horizon

$$
T_{\star}^{\mathrm{f}}=\max \left(\log \left(\frac{6 \beta_{3}}{\left|\beta_{2}\right|}\right), 0\right)
$$

such that the forward curve attains each of the shapes normal, dipped and hd with strictly positive probability at any time $t<T_{\star}$, and each of the shapes normal, dipped with strictly positive probability at any time $t>T_{\star}$. All other shapes are almost surely never attained.

This result shows that more complex initial shapes, like hdh or hd are lost after a deterministic time-horizon under any consistent dynamic evolution of the Svensson family. An analogous result for the yield curve is given by Theorem 6.2, the results are illustrated in Fig. 9. As a direct corollary of Theorem 2.5, we obtain:

Corollary 2.6. The forward curve in the consistent dynamic Svenssonmodel can evolve only within one of the disjoint sets of shapes

$$
\{\text { inverse, humped, } h d h\}, \quad\{\text { normal, dipped, } h d\}
$$

but cannot transition from one set to the other, almost surely with respect to $\mathbb{Q}$.

Since the above results are statements about sets of probability zero (and their complements) it does not matter whether the risk-neutral measure $\mathbb{Q}$ or any other equivalent measure $\mathbb{P}$ is considered. In addition to these results, we show in Section 6.1 how to calculate the exact risk-neutral probability of each attainable shape under consistent dynamic evolution of the Svensson family. Of particular interest is the following ergodicity result, which shows that almost surely, a single shape will dominate the dynamic evolution in the long-run.

Theorem 2.7. Let $\mathrm{S}_{t}(\omega)$ denote the shape of either the yield- or the forwardcurve at time $t>0$ in the consistent dynamic Svensson-model.

![img-5.jpeg](img-5.jpeg)

Figure 5. This diagram shows the shapes that are attained with strictly positive probability for the forward curve in the consistent Svensson model as time $t$ progresses, illustrating Thm. 2.5, Cor. 2.6 and Thm. 2.7. The branch $\beta_{2}>0$ or $\beta_{2}<0$ is selected when the model is calibrated to the initial term structure. Note that each of the times $T_{1}^{t}, T_{*}^{t}$ may be zero, in which case the corresponding part of the diagram collapses.
(1) If $\beta_{2}>0$, then

$$
\lim _{t \rightarrow \infty} 1\left\{\mathrm{~S}_{t}(\omega) \text { is inverse }\right\}=1, \quad \mathbb{Q}-\text { a.s. }
$$

(2) If $\beta_{2}<0$, then

$$
\lim _{t \rightarrow \infty} 1\left\{\mathrm{~S}_{t}(\omega) \text { is normal }\right\}=1, \quad \mathbb{Q}-\text { a.s. }
$$

The above results are illustrated in Fig. 5 for the forward curve and in Fig. 9 for the yield curve.

The remainder of the paper is structured as follows: In Section 3 we discuss some preliminary results on the relation between yield- and forwardcurves, on the Nelson-Siegel subfamily and on total positivity in the Svensson family. In Section 4, we review our main mathematical tool, the envelope method, which was introduced in [KRS23] in the context of the two-factor Vasicek model. In Section 5, we provide the proofs of our main results on the classification and the segmentation problem (Q1,Q2), as well as some refinements of the theorems presented above. In Section 6, we do the same for the consistency problem (Q3). Some auxiliary results are relegated to Appendix A.

# 3. Preliminaries and basic results 

3.1. Yield curve vs. forward curve. Let $f(x, \beta)$ denote the forward curve in dependency on time-to-maturity $x$ and the parameter vector $\beta$. Then the associated yield curve is given by

$$
y(x, \beta)=\frac{1}{x} \int_{0}^{x} f(y, \beta) d y
$$

and it can be considered as a running average (in time-to-maturity) of the forward curve. Consequently, the shape of the yield curve will be 'smoother' than the shape of the forward curve. In fact, we have the following result from $[\mathrm{KR} 21]:^{5}$

Theorem 3.1 (See [KR21, Thm. 3.4]). The following holds for the relation between yield curve and forward curve:
(1) the initial slope of yield- and forward curve has the same sign;
(2) the number of local extrema of the yield curve is less or equal to the number of local extrema of the forward curve;
(3) if the number of local extrema is the same, the also the type (dip/hump) coincides.

For this reason, many results obtained for the forward curve have immediate consequences for the yield curve. Other results, for example on the segmentation of the parameter space, have to be shown separately for yield curve and forward curve. However, usually the same method can be used for both with minor adaptations. Using the Svensson-parametrization (1.2) for the forward curve, one immediately sees that the corresponding yield curve

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Phi_{S}(x)= & \beta_{0}+\frac{\beta_{1} \tau_{1}}{x}\left(1-e^{-x / \tau_{1}}\right)+\beta_{2}\left(\frac{\tau_{1}}{x}\left(1-e^{-x / \tau_{1}}\right)-e^{-x / \tau_{1}}\right)+ \\
& +\beta_{3}\left(\frac{\tau_{2}}{x}\left(1-e^{-x / \tau_{2}}\right)-e^{-x / \tau_{2}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

will still be a linear function of the parameter vector $\beta$ with only the basis functions transformed by (3.1). Generally, most of our results will be obtained first for the forward curve and then be transferred to the yield curve; some useful Lemmas are given in Appendix A.
3.2. The Nelson-Siegel family. For the Nelson-Siegel family, questions Q1 and Q2 can be solved directly, using elementary means. Looking at the forward curve, it is sufficient to take the time-derivative of (1.1) to obtain

$$
\phi_{N S}^{\prime}(x)=\frac{1}{\tau}\left(\beta_{2}\left(1-\frac{x}{\tau}\right)-\beta_{1}\right) \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau}\right)
$$

Clearly, this derivative is zero at $x \in(0, \infty)$ if and only if

$$
x=\tau\left(1-\frac{\beta_{1}}{\beta_{2}}\right)
$$

and, if it has a zero, it also changes sign at this point. Together with Theorem 3.1 this leads to the following simple result:

Theorem 3.2. In the Nelson-Siegel family only the shapes normal, inverse, humped and dipped are attainable for the forward curve. The same holds true for the yield curve. The parameter space segmentation is given in Table 2 .
3.3. Basic results on the Svensson family. For the Svensson family, the direct approach used for the Nelson-Siegel family runs into problems. Due to the additional basis function it is no longer possible to determine the zeroes of $\phi_{S}^{\prime}$ explicitly, as it was in the Nelson-Siegel model. Nevertheless, some basic results can be obtained from the theory of Tchebycheff systems; see [KS66, Kar68] for general results and [KR21] for an application to interest rate models. From [KS66] we recall that a family $\left(u_{1}, \ldots, u_{n}\right)$ of continuous functions on a closed interval $[a, b]$ is a Tchebycheff system if

$$
\operatorname{det}\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
u_{1}\left(x_{1}\right) & u_{2}\left(x_{1}\right) & \ldots & u_{n}\left(x_{1}\right) \\
\vdots & \vdots & & \vdots \\
u_{1}\left(x_{n}\right) & u_{2}\left(x_{n}\right) & \ldots & u_{n}\left(x_{n}\right)
\end{array}\right)>0
$$

holds for all $a \leq x_{1}<x_{2}<\cdots<x_{n} \leq b$. When the family is defined on $[0, \infty)$ it is called a Tchebycheff system if it is a Tchebycheff system on $[0, A]$ for every $A>0$. The key property of Tchebycheff systems is the following:
Lemma 3.3. Let $\left(u_{1}, \ldots, u_{n}\right)$ be a Tchebycheff system on $[0, \infty)$ and let $\boldsymbol{\beta}=\left(\beta_{1}, \ldots, \beta_{n}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{n} \backslash\{0\}$. Then the function

$$
u(x)=\beta_{1} u_{1}(x)+\cdots \beta_{n} u_{n}(x)
$$

has at most $n-1$ zeroes in $[0, \infty)$.
Differentiating (1.2) with respect to $x$, we find that

$$
\phi_{S}^{\prime}(x)=\left(\beta_{2}-\beta_{1}\right) f_{1}(x)-\beta_{2} f_{2}(x)+\beta_{3} f_{3}(x)-\beta_{3} f_{4}(x)
$$

where

$$
\left(f_{1}(x), f_{2}(x), f_{3}(x), f_{4}(x)\right)=\left(\frac{1}{\tau_{1}} e^{-\frac{x}{\tau_{1}}}, \frac{x}{\tau_{1}^{2}} e^{-\frac{x}{\tau_{1}}}, \frac{1}{\tau_{2}} e^{-\frac{x}{\tau_{2}}}, \frac{x}{\tau_{2}^{2}} e^{-\frac{x}{\tau_{2}}}\right)
$$

It is not difficult to show that these basis functions $\left(f_{1}, f_{2}, f_{3}, f_{4}\right)$ of the differentiated forward curve in the Svensson family (as well as their counterparts for the yield curve) form a Tchebycheff system; see Lemma A.1. This immediately leads to a simple proof of Theorem 2.2:

Proof of Theorem 2.2. The derivative $\phi_{S}^{\prime}$ of the Svensson curve $\phi_{S}$ is a linear combination of the functions $\left(f_{1}, f_{2}, f_{3}, f_{4}\right)$. The derivative of the Bliss curve $\left(\beta_{2}=0\right)$ is a linear combination of $\left(f_{1}, f_{3}, f_{4}\right)$. The derivative of the NelsonSiegel curve $\left(\beta_{3}=0\right)$ is a linear combination of $\left(f_{1}, f_{2}\right)$. By Lemma A. 1 $\left(f_{1}, f_{2}, f_{3}, f_{4}\right),\left(f_{1}, f_{3}, f_{4}\right)$, and $\left(f_{1}, f_{2}\right)$ are Tchebycheff systems. Hence, in case of the forward curve, the claim follows by applying Lemma 3.3. For the yield curve, it then suffices to apply Theorem 3.1.

# 4. The envelope method 

We review the envelope method for the classification of term structure shapes $(\mathbf{Q 1})$ and the segmentation of the parameter space $\Theta^{\prime}(\mathbf{Q 2})$. This method was introduced in [KRS23] in the context of the two-factor Vasicek model, but can be applied in far more general settings.
4.1. Enveloping a family of lines. Assuming for now that $\beta_{3} \neq 0$ we differentiate (2.1) and write it in the form

$$
\phi_{S}^{\prime}(x)=\beta_{3}\left\{a_{\mathrm{f}}(x)+b_{\mathrm{f}}(x) \gamma_{I}+c_{\mathrm{f}}(x) \gamma_{I I}\right\}
$$

with coefficients given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
& a_{\mathrm{f}}(x)=f_{3}(x)-f_{4}(x)=\frac{1}{\tau_{2}}\left(1-\frac{x}{\tau_{2}}\right) \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau_{2}}\right) \\
& b_{\mathrm{f}}(x)=f_{1}(x)-f_{2}(x)=\frac{1}{\tau_{1}}\left(1-\frac{x}{\tau_{1}}\right) \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau_{1}}\right) \\
& c_{\mathrm{f}}(x)=-f_{1}(x)=-\frac{1}{\tau_{1}} \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau_{1}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Note that the same structure (4.1) holds for the yield curve, but with the different basis functions

$$
\begin{aligned}
& a_{\mathrm{y}}(x)=\frac{1}{x^{2}}\left(\left(x+\tau_{2}\right) e^{-x / \tau_{2}}-\tau_{2}\right)+\frac{1}{\tau_{2}} e^{-x / \tau_{2}} \\
& b_{\mathrm{y}}(x)=\frac{1}{x^{2}}\left(\left(x+\tau_{1}\right) e^{-x / \tau_{1}}-\tau_{1}\right)+\frac{1}{\tau_{1}} e^{-x / \tau_{1}} \\
& c_{\mathrm{y}}(x)=\frac{1}{x^{2}}\left(\left(x+\tau_{1}\right) e^{-x / \tau_{1}}-\tau_{1}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

We will now drop the subscripts f and y and simply use $(a, b, c)$ to denote either of $\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}, b_{\mathrm{f}}, c_{\mathrm{f}}\right)$ or $\left(a_{\mathrm{y}}, b_{\mathrm{y}}, c_{\mathrm{y}}\right)$. Later, when it becomes necessary to distinguish between the two cases, we add superscripts and subscripts again. It is easy to verify that $c(x) \neq 0$ for all $x \in(0, \infty)$; hence, for any $x \in(0, \infty)$,

$$
\ell_{x}=\left\{\left(\gamma_{I}, \gamma_{I I}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{2} \mid a(x)+b(x) \gamma_{I}+c(x) \gamma_{I I}=0\right\}
$$

# 6. Analysis of the consistent dynamic Svensson family 

As outlined in Section 2.3, we now consider a dynamic version of the Svensson-model, where the extended parameter vector $\tilde{\beta}=\left(\beta_{0}, \beta_{1}, \beta_{2}, \beta_{3}, \tau_{1}, \tau_{2}\right)$ is replaced by an Ito process $(\tilde{\beta}(t))_{t \geq 0}$ of the form (2.4). From [Fil00] (see also [Fil09, Prop. 9.5]) the only consistent dynamics of this process are of the following form

$$
\begin{aligned}
\beta_{0}(t) & =\beta_{0} \\
\mathrm{~d} \beta_{1}(t) & =\left(\frac{\beta_{2}}{\tau_{1}} e^{-t / \tau_{1}}+\frac{2 \beta_{3}}{\tau_{1}} e^{-2 t / \tau_{1}}-\frac{1}{\tau_{1}} \beta_{1}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t+\frac{\sqrt{2 \beta_{3}}}{\tau_{1}} e^{-t / \tau_{1}} \mathrm{~d} W^{*}(t) \\
\beta_{2}(t) & =\beta_{2} \exp \left(-\frac{1}{\tau_{1}} t\right) \\
\beta_{3}(t) & =\beta_{3} \exp \left(-\frac{2}{\tau_{1}} t\right) \\
\tau_{1}(t) & =\tau_{1} \\
\tau_{2}(t) & =\frac{\tau_{1}}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $W^{*}$ is a one-dimensional $\mathbb{Q}$-Brownian motion obtained as a transformation of the original multivariate $\mathbb{Q}$-Brownian motion $W$; see [Fil09, Ch. 9] for details. We first observe that $\beta_{3}$ must be greater than 0 for the dynamics of $\beta_{1}(t)$ to be well-defined. This is already a significant restriction, since it implies per Theorem 2.3 that the shapes dh and dhd are not attainable. As a next step we transform to $\gamma$-coordinates, see (2.2), setting

$$
\left(\gamma_{\mathrm{I}}(t), \gamma_{\mathrm{II}}(t)\right)=\left(\frac{\beta_{2}(t)}{\beta_{3}(t)}, \frac{\beta_{1}(t)}{\beta_{3}(t)}\right)
$$

which, by Ito's formula, implies

$$
\begin{aligned}
\gamma_{\mathrm{I}}(t) & =\frac{\beta_{2}}{\beta_{3}} e^{t / \tau_{1}} \\
\mathrm{~d} \gamma_{\mathrm{II}}(t) & =\frac{1}{\tau_{1}}\left(2+\gamma_{\mathrm{I}}(t)+\gamma_{\mathrm{II}}(t)\right) \mathrm{d} t+\frac{1}{\tau_{1}} \sqrt{\frac{2}{\beta_{3}(t)}} \mathrm{d} W_{t}^{*}, \quad \gamma_{\mathrm{II}}(0)=\frac{\beta_{1}}{\beta_{3}}
\end{aligned}
$$

In the parameter-space picture (see Fig. 2A), the coordinate $\gamma_{\mathrm{I}}(t)$ describes a monotone movement along the horizontal axis, which is increasing if $\beta_{2}>0$ and decreasing if $\beta_{2}<0$. The coordinate $\gamma_{\text {II }}(t)$ follows a non-degenerate Gaussian process, which is supported on the whole real line for any $t>0$. We conclude the following:

Lemma 6.1. Under the consistent dynamic evolution of the Svensson family, a shape $S$ of the forward curve is attained with strictly positive probability at time $t>0$, if and only if the vertical line defined by $\gamma_{\mathrm{I}}(t)=\frac{\beta_{2}}{\beta_{3}} e^{t / \tau_{1}}$ in the $\left(\gamma_{\mathrm{I}}, \gamma_{\mathrm{II}}\right)$-plane intersects the region $R_{i}$ associated to shape $S$.

To obtain Theorem 2.5, it remains to determine the possible intersections. We proceed separately for the forward curve and the yield curve.

# Appendix A. Auxiliary results 

Lemma A.1. Let $\tau_{1} \neq \tau_{2}$ be positive numbers. The system

$$
\left(f_{1}(x), f_{2}(x), f_{3}(x), f_{4}(x)\right)=\left(\frac{1}{\tau_{1}} e^{-\frac{x}{\tau_{1}}}, \frac{x}{\tau_{1}^{2}} e^{-\frac{x}{\tau_{1}}}, \frac{1}{\tau_{2}} e^{-\frac{x}{\tau_{2}}}, \frac{x}{\tau_{2}^{2}} e^{-\frac{x}{\tau_{2}}}\right)
$$

and its subsystems $\left(f_{1}, f_{2}\right)$ and $\left(f_{1}, f_{3}, f_{4}\right)$ are Tchebycheff systems on $\mathbb{R}$.
Proof. By [KS66, Ch. XI, Thm. 1.1], the system $\left(f_{1}, f_{2}, f_{3}, f_{4}\right)$ forms an extended complete Tchebycheff system (ECT-system) on $\mathbb{R}$, since

$$
\begin{aligned}
W\left(f_{1}\right)(x) & =\frac{1}{\tau_{1}} \exp \left(-\frac{x}{\tau_{1}}\right)>0 \\
W\left(f_{1}, f_{2}\right)(x) & =\frac{1}{\tau_{1}^{3}} \exp \left(-x \frac{2}{\tau_{1}}\right)>0 \\
W\left(f_{1}, f_{2}, f_{3}\right)(x) & =\frac{\left(\tau_{2}-\tau_{1}\right)^{2}}{\tau_{1}^{5} \tau_{2}^{3}} \exp \left(-x\left(\frac{2}{\tau_{1}}+\frac{1}{\tau_{2}}\right)\right)>0 \\
W\left(f_{1}, f_{2}, f_{3}, f_{4}\right)(x) & =\frac{\left(\tau_{2}-\tau_{1}\right)^{4}}{\tau_{1}^{7} \tau_{2}^{7}} \exp \left(-x\left(\frac{2}{\tau_{1}}+\frac{2}{\tau_{2}}\right)\right)>0
\end{aligned}
$$

It is therefore in particular a Tchebycheff system. From the calculations we conclude that also $\left(f_{1}, f_{2}\right)$ is a Tchebycheff system. It furthermore holds that

$$
\begin{aligned}
W\left(f_{1}, \pm f_{3}\right)(x) & = \pm \frac{\left(\tau_{2}-\tau_{1}\right)}{\tau_{1}^{2} \tau_{2}^{2}} \exp \left(-x\left(\frac{1}{\tau_{1}}+\frac{1}{\tau_{2}}\right)\right) \\
W\left(f_{1}, \pm f_{3}, \pm f_{4}\right)(x) & =\frac{\left(\tau_{2}-\tau_{1}\right)^{2}}{\tau_{1}^{3} \tau_{2}^{4}} \exp \left(-x\left(\frac{2}{\tau_{1}}+\frac{1}{\tau_{2}}\right)\right)>0
\end{aligned}
$$

hence (in dependency on the sign of $\tau_{2}-\tau_{1}$ ) one of the systems $\left(f_{1}, f_{3}, f_{4}\right)$ and $\left(f_{1},-f_{3},-f_{4}\right)$ is an ECT-system on $\mathbb{R}$. Again, it follows that $\left(f_{1}, f_{3}, f_{4}\right)$ is a Tchebycheff system.

The following Lemma on the relationship between the envelopes and the Wronskians associated to the forward curve and to the yield curve was shown (with exception of claims (d) and (f)) in [KRS23] in the context of the

two-dimensional Vasicek model. The proof, however, was only based on the family of lines defined through (4.4) and the assumptions discussed in Section 4.2

Lemma A. 2 (See also Lemma A. 1 in [KRS23]). Suppose that (A1')-(A4) hold true for $\mathcal{F}_{(0, T)}^{\mathrm{f}}$ with $T \in(0, \infty]$. Then the following holds for the envelopes $\eta_{\mathrm{f}}$ and $\eta_{\mathrm{y}}$ and for the Wronskians associated to the forward curve and to the yield curve:
(a) The envelopes $\eta_{\mathrm{f}}$ and $\eta_{\mathrm{y}}$ start in the same point, i.e., $\eta_{\mathrm{f}}(0)=\eta_{\mathrm{y}}(0)$;
(b) The endpoint of $\eta_{\mathrm{y}}(T)$ is the intersection of $\ell_{T}^{\mathrm{f}}$ and $\ell_{T}^{\mathrm{y}}$;
(c) Every cusp point of $\eta_{\mathrm{y}}$ is incident to $\eta_{\mathrm{f}}$.
(d) The Wronskian $W\left(b_{\mathrm{y}}, c_{\mathrm{y}}\right)$ has no zeroes on $(0, T)$ and has the same sign as $W\left(b_{\mathrm{f}}, c_{\mathrm{f}}\right)$;
(e) The number of zeros of $W\left(a_{\mathrm{y}}, b_{\mathrm{y}}, c_{\mathrm{y}}\right)$ is less or equal than the number of zeros of $W\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}, b_{\mathrm{f}}, c_{\mathrm{f}}\right)$ on $(0, T)$
(f) $W\left(a_{\mathrm{y}}, b_{\mathrm{y}}, c_{\mathrm{y}}\right)(0)=\frac{1}{24} W\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}, b_{\mathrm{f}}, c_{\mathrm{f}}\right)(0)$

Proof. All parts, except (d) and (f) have been shown in Lemma A. 1 in [KRS23]. Regarding part (d), we obtain from the calculations in the proof of [KRS23, Lem. A.1] and Eq. (3.1) the relationship

$$
W\left(b_{\mathrm{y}}, c_{\mathrm{y}}\right)(x)=\frac{1}{x}\left|\begin{array}{ll}
b_{\mathrm{y}}(x) & c_{\mathrm{y}}(x) \\
b_{\mathrm{f}}(x) & c_{\mathrm{f}}(x)
\end{array}\right|=\frac{1}{x^{3}} \int_{0}^{x} \zeta\left|\begin{array}{ll}
b_{\mathrm{f}}(\zeta) & c_{\mathrm{f}}(\zeta) \\
b_{\mathrm{f}}(x) & c_{\mathrm{f}}(x)
\end{array}\right| \mathrm{d} \zeta
$$

From [Kar68, Ch. 2 §2, Thm. 2.3] and the assumptions that $c_{\mathrm{f}}$ and $W\left(b_{\mathrm{f}}, c_{\mathrm{f}}\right)$ have no zero in $(0, T)$ we deduce that the determinant under the integral also has no zero and the same sign as $W\left(b_{\mathrm{f}}, c_{\mathrm{f}}\right)$. It follows that the same must hold for $W\left(b_{\mathrm{y}}, c_{\mathrm{y}}\right)$. Regarding (f), it follows from the calculations in the proof of [KRS23, Lem. A.1] that

$$
g_{\mathrm{y}}(0)=\frac{g_{\mathrm{f}}(0)}{2}, \quad g_{\mathrm{y}}^{\prime}(0)=\frac{g_{\mathrm{f}}^{\prime}(0)}{3}, \quad g_{\mathrm{y}}^{\prime \prime}(0)=\frac{g_{\mathrm{f}}^{\prime \prime}(0)}{4}
$$

holds for any choice of $g \in\{a, b, c\}$. Applying this to the Wronskian $W\left(a_{\mathrm{y}}, b_{\mathrm{y}}, c_{\mathrm{y}}\right)(0)$, claim (f) follows.

Lemma A.3. Let $a, b, c \in \mathbb{R}$. If $b c \geq 0$, then the equation $(x+a) \mathrm{e}^{b x}=c$ is solved by

$$
x=\frac{\mathcal{W}_{0}\left(b c \cdot \mathrm{e}^{a b}\right)}{b}-a
$$

where $\mathcal{W}_{0}$ is the 0 -th branch of the Lambert $\mathcal{W}$-function. If $b c<0$ and $|b c| \leq e^{a b-1}$, then the solution takes the same form, but using the branch $\mathcal{W}_{-1}$ of the Lambert $\mathcal{W}$-function. In all other cases, there is no real solution.

Proof. The Lambert $\mathcal{W}$-function $\left[\mathrm{CGH}^{+} 96\right]$ is implicitly defined for all $x \geq$ $1 / e$ by

$$
\mathcal{W}(x) \mathrm{e}^{\mathcal{W}(x)}=x
$$

where $x \geq 0$ yields the branch $\mathcal{W}_{0}$ and $x \in[-1 / e, 0)$ the branch $\mathcal{W}_{-1}$. Using the chain of equivalences

$$
\begin{aligned}
& (x+a) \mathrm{e}^{b x}=c \\
\Leftrightarrow & (b x+a b) \mathrm{e}^{b x+a b}=b c \cdot \mathrm{e}^{a b} \\
\Leftrightarrow & b x+a b=\mathcal{W}\left(b c \cdot \mathrm{e}^{a b}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

the desired result follows.

abstract:
We examine the shapes attainable by the forward- and yield-curve in the
widely-used Svensson family, including the Nelson-Siegel and Bliss subfamilies.
We provide a complete classification of all attainable shapes and partition the
parameter space of each family according to these shapes. Building upon these
results, we then examine the consistent dynamic evolution of the Svensson
family under absence of arbitrage. Our analysis shows that consistent dynamics
further restrict the set of attainable shapes, and we demonstrate that certain
complex shapes can no longer appear after a deterministic time horizon.
Moreover a single shape (either inverse of normal curves) must dominate in the
long-run.
